{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Do focused WEB research (WebSearch + WebFetch; cite URLs). Do not answer from memory alone.\n\nCONTEXT: A local self-improving agent (\"Yogi\") uses qwen3:8b (via Ollama) + nomic-embed-text. It tried to certify token-space *skill transfer*: a made-up operation `a ⊕ b = a*b + a + b`, tested on fresh operands. Cold (rule unknown) the model scores 0.00 (correct). With the learned RULE injected into context via memory retrieval it scored only 0.10 — far below a working transfer (~0.8+). Suspects: (1) the proposer prefixes `/no_think`, so the model can't do the step-by-step arithmetic to APPLY the rule; (2) retrieval miss on the rare `⊕` symbol; (3) qwen3:8b is a weak in-context learner.\n\nRESEARCH these and recommend the best fixes/variations:\n1. **Thinking vs no-think for rule application / arithmetic on qwen3 (and small models).** Does enabling reasoning (qwen3 thinking mode / chain-of-thought) materially improve applying an in-context rule? How much max_tokens does thinking need? Any data on qwen3 `/think` vs `/no_think` for multi-step arithmetic. Trade-offs (latency, memory).\n2. **How to format an in-context skill so a small model reliably applies it.** Worked examples / few-shot in the skill, explicit step-by-step template, \"show your work then answer\", output-format constraints. What formats most improve in-context rule-following for 7-8B models?\n3. **Retrieval reliability for symbolic / rare-token queries** with a sentence-embedding model (nomic-embed-text): do queries containing rare symbols (⊕) retrieve a rule note reliably? Should the skill be keyed/retrieved differently (keyword + embedding hybrid), or injected deterministically when a task-class is detected?\n4. **Other variations to make token-space skill-transfer actually work at 8B**: self-consistency / multiple samples + vote, larger student vs distillation, simpler vs richer skill notes, separating \"retrieve\" from \"apply\", verification/self-check steps.\n5. **Designing a transfer benchmark that's both cold-failing AND applicable**: tasks where a told rule reliably lifts a small model (so a positive result is achievable), vs tasks where even with the rule the model fails (avoid those for a first certification).\n\nEND WITH a concrete, prioritized RECOMMENDATION for Yogi: the specific config + skill-format + bench changes most likely to turn the 0.10 into a certifiable transfer lift on qwen3:8b at 16 GB — ordered cheapest-first. Cite URLs throughout. Return findings only; do not edit files."},"uuid":"4d920b85-4843-40de-8882-264660cf2b9b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:45:12.937Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
