{"parentUuid":"eaf71305-715f-430f-8e95-95936150b92f","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01M46ai8R9RJQvvec93XHFmW","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"qwen3 8b thinking mode max_tokens budget recommended reasoning length\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Qwen3 VL 8B Thinking - API Pricing & Benchmarks | OpenRouter\",\"url\":\"https://openrouter.ai/qwen/qwen3-vl-8b-thinking\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3: Think Deeper, Act Faster | Qwen\",\"url\":\"https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen3/\"},{\"title\":\"Thinking Budget Control (Thinking-Token Limiter) — NVIDIA NIM for Large Language Models (LLMs)\",\"url\":\"https://docs.nvidia.com/nim/large-language-models/latest/thinking-budget-control.html\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3-VL-8B Instruct vs Thinking: Which to Use (2026)\",\"url\":\"https://codersera.com/blog/qwen3-vl-8b-instruct-vs-qwen3-vl-8b-thinking-2025-guide/\"},{\"title\":\"Thinking Token limit setting - General - vLLM Forums\",\"url\":\"https://discuss.vllm.ai/t/thinking-token-limit-setting/2400\"},{\"title\":\"[Bug] thinking_budget not enforced for Qwen3.6 — reasoning consumes all max_tokens · Issue #25536 · sgl-project/sglang\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/issues/25536\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3/docs/source/getting_started/thinking_budget.md at main · QwenLM/Qwen3\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/QwenLM/Qwen3/blob/main/docs/source/getting_started/thinking_budget.md\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3-Max-Thinking: Hands-On With the Largest LLM in the World | DataCamp\",\"url\":\"https://www.datacamp.com/tutorial/qwen3-max-thinking\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Qwen3-8B thinking mode and token budgets:\n\n## Thinking Budget Basics\n\nThinking budget control (also known as reasoning budget control) is a feature that limits how many \"thinking\" tokens a model can generate before it must start producing its final answer. Qwen3 exhibits scalable and smooth performance improvements that are directly correlated with the computational reasoning budget allocated, enabling users to configure task-specific budgets with greater ease, achieving a more optimal balance between cost efficiency and inference quality.\n\n## Recommended Settings for Qwen3-8B\n\nAccording to the official documentation, the thinking_budget should be smaller than the maximum new tokens (max_tokens parameter). A common example shown in the code is using a thinking_budget of 512 with max_tokens of 1024.\n\n## Max Tokens and Context\n\nQwen3-VL-8B has a 256,000 token context window, with a maximum output of 32,768 tokens.\n\n## Important Considerations\n\nRate-limit by output tokens, not just requests — Thinking can blow your budget on a single hard prompt. For cost estimation, thinking mode can generate 2–3x more output tokens per query for hard problems.\n\nThe recommended approach is to set your thinking_budget as a fraction of your total max_tokens (e.g., 512 for thinking with 1024 total), adjusting based on your specific use case complexity and cost constraints.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"f0f37421-61e5-403c-b054-31d20f19845b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:45:28.496Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"qwen3 8b thinking mode max_tokens budget recommended reasoning length","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_013Uvi5kJ67WyCaZPAWSGxZu","content":[{"title":"Qwen3 VL 8B Thinking - API Pricing & Benchmarks | OpenRouter","url":"https://openrouter.ai/qwen/qwen3-vl-8b-thinking"},{"title":"Qwen3: Think Deeper, Act Faster | Qwen","url":"https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen3/"},{"title":"Thinking Budget Control (Thinking-Token Limiter) — NVIDIA NIM for Large Language Models (LLMs)","url":"https://docs.nvidia.com/nim/large-language-models/latest/thinking-budget-control.html"},{"title":"Qwen3-VL-8B Instruct vs Thinking: Which to Use (2026)","url":"https://codersera.com/blog/qwen3-vl-8b-instruct-vs-qwen3-vl-8b-thinking-2025-guide/"},{"title":"Thinking Token limit setting - General - vLLM Forums","url":"https://discuss.vllm.ai/t/thinking-token-limit-setting/2400"},{"title":"[Bug] thinking_budget not enforced for Qwen3.6 — reasoning consumes all max_tokens · Issue #25536 · sgl-project/sglang","url":"https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/issues/25536"},{"title":"Qwen3/docs/source/getting_started/thinking_budget.md at main · QwenLM/Qwen3","url":"https://github.com/QwenLM/Qwen3/blob/main/docs/source/getting_started/thinking_budget.md"},{"title":"Qwen3-Max-Thinking: Hands-On With the Largest LLM in the World | DataCamp","url":"https://www.datacamp.com/tutorial/qwen3-max-thinking"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about Qwen3-8B thinking mode and token budgets:\n\n## Thinking Budget Basics\n\nThinking budget control (also known as reasoning budget control) is a feature that limits how many \"thinking\" tokens a model can generate before it must start producing its final answer. Qwen3 exhibits scalable and smooth performance improvements that are directly correlated with the computational reasoning budget allocated, enabling users to configure task-specific budgets with greater ease, achieving a more optimal balance between cost efficiency and inference quality.\n\n## Recommended Settings for Qwen3-8B\n\nAccording to the official documentation, the thinking_budget should be smaller than the maximum new tokens (max_tokens parameter). A common example shown in the code is using a thinking_budget of 512 with max_tokens of 1024.\n\n## Max Tokens and Context\n\nQwen3-VL-8B has a 256,000 token context window, with a maximum output of 32,768 tokens.\n\n## Important Considerations\n\nRate-limit by output tokens, not just requests — Thinking can blow your budget on a single hard prompt. For cost estimation, thinking mode can generate 2–3x more output tokens per query for hard problems.\n\nThe recommended approach is to set your thinking_budget as a fraction of your total max_tokens (e.g., 512 for thinking with 1024 total), adjusting based on your specific use case complexity and cost constraints."],"durationSeconds":7.451801667000167,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"eaf71305-715f-430f-8e95-95936150b92f","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"38d1d507-8f15-4a36-b9e7-b168606c2f86","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017J5HRdToJf82J7NXTLe82L","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"qwen3 /think vs /no_think thinking mode arithmetic reasoning multi-step accuracy\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Efficient Reasoning via Thought-Training and Thought-Free Inference\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.03408\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3 - How to Run & Fine-tune | Unsloth Documentation\",\"url\":\"https://unsloth.ai/docs/models/tutorials/qwen3-how-to-run-and-fine-tune\"},{\"title\":\"qwen3:4b: Can't turn off thinking · Issue #12917 · ollama/ollama\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ollama/ollama/issues/12917\"},{\"title\":\"Wait, We Don't Need to \\\"Wait\\\"! Removing Thinking Tokens Improves Reasoning Efficiency\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.08343\"},{\"title\":\"Reasoning Models Better Express Their Confidence\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.14489v2\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen/Qwen3-0.6B · Hugging Face\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-0.6B\"},{\"title\":\"Efficient Reasoning via Thought-Training and Thought-Free Inference\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.03408v1\"},{\"title\":\"Explicit Reasoning Makes Better Judges: A Systematic Study on Accuracy, Efficiency, and Robustness\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.13332\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3 Instruct vs Thinking vs Coder: Model Selection Guide\",\"url\":\"https://fireworks.ai/blog/qwen-3-decoded\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3: Think Deeper, Act Faster | Qwen\",\"url\":\"https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen3/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Qwen3's /think vs /no_think thinking modes and their impact on arithmetic reasoning and multi-step accuracy:\n\n## Key Differences Between Modes\n\nYou can add /think and /no_think to user prompts or system messages to switch the model's thinking mode from turn to turn. In thinking mode, the model will generate an extra <think>...</think> block before the final answer — this lets it \"plan\" and sharpen its responses. Enabling non-thinking will make Qwen3 skip all the thinking steps and behave like a normal LLM. This mode will provide final responses directly — no <think> blocks, no chain-of-thought.\n\n## Accuracy Impact on Arithmetic Reasoning\n\nThe accuracy trade-offs are substantial:\n\nGSM8K drops from 93.0% to 90.3%, and AIME24 from 76.6% to 43.3% when adding no-think training data to Qwen3-8B. Increasing the No-Think ratio consistently shortens model outputs but monotonically reduces accuracy. Even 1% No-Think materially hurts reasoning fidelity, indicating high sensitivity to non-reasoning supervision.\n\n## Multi-Step Reasoning\n\nThinking mode achieves more with less compute. Across all model scales (0.6B, 1.7B, and 4B), thinking model consistently achieves the highest accuracy. In contrast, thinking model offers a much more efficient performance-cost trade-off, delivering superior accuracy with only a modest 1.3-2.9x increase in FLOPs.\n\nThe research shows that the thinking mode is particularly critical for complex mathematical reasoning, with the non-thinking mode producing dramatic accuracy drops on challenging benchmarks like AIME.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"6fb7e38f-8e6f-4efc-8cdb-5bf33d235eb5","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:45:31.674Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"qwen3 /think vs /no_think thinking mode arithmetic reasoning multi-step accuracy","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_013nkPEvhHuo6Le7u9tEPXzd","content":[{"title":"Efficient Reasoning via Thought-Training and Thought-Free Inference","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.03408"},{"title":"Qwen3 - How to Run & Fine-tune | Unsloth Documentation","url":"https://unsloth.ai/docs/models/tutorials/qwen3-how-to-run-and-fine-tune"},{"title":"qwen3:4b: Can't turn off thinking · Issue #12917 · ollama/ollama","url":"https://github.com/ollama/ollama/issues/12917"},{"title":"Wait, We Don't Need to \"Wait\"! Removing Thinking Tokens Improves Reasoning Efficiency","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.08343"},{"title":"Reasoning Models Better Express Their Confidence","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.14489v2"},{"title":"Qwen/Qwen3-0.6B · Hugging Face","url":"https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-0.6B"},{"title":"Efficient Reasoning via Thought-Training and Thought-Free Inference","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.03408v1"},{"title":"Explicit Reasoning Makes Better Judges: A Systematic Study on Accuracy, Efficiency, and Robustness","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.13332"},{"title":"Qwen3 Instruct vs Thinking vs Coder: Model Selection Guide","url":"https://fireworks.ai/blog/qwen-3-decoded"},{"title":"Qwen3: Think Deeper, Act Faster | Qwen","url":"https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen3/"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about Qwen3's /think vs /no_think thinking modes and their impact on arithmetic reasoning and multi-step accuracy:\n\n## Key Differences Between Modes\n\nYou can add /think and /no_think to user prompts or system messages to switch the model's thinking mode from turn to turn. In thinking mode, the model will generate an extra <think>...</think> block before the final answer — this lets it \"plan\" and sharpen its responses. Enabling non-thinking will make Qwen3 skip all the thinking steps and behave like a normal LLM. This mode will provide final responses directly — no <think> blocks, no chain-of-thought.\n\n## Accuracy Impact on Arithmetic Reasoning\n\nThe accuracy trade-offs are substantial:\n\nGSM8K drops from 93.0% to 90.3%, and AIME24 from 76.6% to 43.3% when adding no-think training data to Qwen3-8B. Increasing the No-Think ratio consistently shortens model outputs but monotonically reduces accuracy. Even 1% No-Think materially hurts reasoning fidelity, indicating high sensitivity to non-reasoning supervision.\n\n## Multi-Step Reasoning\n\nThinking mode achieves more with less compute. Across all model scales (0.6B, 1.7B, and 4B), thinking model consistently achieves the highest accuracy. In contrast, thinking model offers a much more efficient performance-cost trade-off, delivering superior accuracy with only a modest 1.3-2.9x increase in FLOPs.\n\nThe research shows that the thinking mode is particularly critical for complex mathematical reasoning, with the non-thinking mode producing dramatic accuracy drops on challenging benchmarks like AIME."],"durationSeconds":10.83552199999988,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"38d1d507-8f15-4a36-b9e7-b168606c2f86","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
