{"parentUuid":"f0521d81-a20f-41c8-bdae-2bbd29900a5f","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0174V9cBFZnGfpuad3X5Pz7d","type":"tool_result","content":"# Qwen3 Thinking vs Non-Thinking Mode: Key Specifics\n\n## Accuracy Differences on Math Benchmarks\nThe blog post does not provide specific accuracy comparisons between thinking and non-thinking modes on benchmarks like GSM8K, AIME, or MATH.\n\n## Sampling Parameters\nNo recommended sampling parameters (temperature, top_p, top_k) are specified for either mode in the documentation.\n\n## Generation Length & Thinking Budget\nThe only quantitative guidance provided is: \"you can add /think and /no_think to user prompts or system messages to switch the model's thinking mode from turn to turn.\" The code examples show `max_new_tokens=32768` as a general setting, but this applies to both modes.\n\n## Soft Switch Behavior\nThe documentation explains that users have \"a soft switch mechanism that allows users to dynamically control the model's behavior.\" Key details:\n\n- The `/think` and `/no_think` commands enable mode switching within conversations\n- \"The model will follow the most recent instruction in multi-turn conversations\"\n- When `enable_thinking=True` (the default), users can toggle modes per turn using these commands\n- The multi-turn example demonstrates this capability but shows no performance metrics\n\nThe blog emphasizes flexibility but omits the technical specifications you've requested."}]},"uuid":"1a6cb7a7-d5b0-452a-a35a-aacc40c52782","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:45:44.464Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":71638,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Qwen3 Thinking vs Non-Thinking Mode: Key Specifics\n\n## Accuracy Differences on Math Benchmarks\nThe blog post does not provide specific accuracy comparisons between thinking and non-thinking modes on benchmarks like GSM8K, AIME, or MATH.\n\n## Sampling Parameters\nNo recommended sampling parameters (temperature, top_p, top_k) are specified for either mode in the documentation.\n\n## Generation Length & Thinking Budget\nThe only quantitative guidance provided is: \"you can add /think and /no_think to user prompts or system messages to switch the model's thinking mode from turn to turn.\" The code examples show `max_new_tokens=32768` as a general setting, but this applies to both modes.\n\n## Soft Switch Behavior\nThe documentation explains that users have \"a soft switch mechanism that allows users to dynamically control the model's behavior.\" Key details:\n\n- The `/think` and `/no_think` commands enable mode switching within conversations\n- \"The model will follow the most recent instruction in multi-turn conversations\"\n- When `enable_thinking=True` (the default), users can toggle modes per turn using these commands\n- The multi-turn example demonstrates this capability but shows no performance metrics\n\nThe blog emphasizes flexibility but omits the technical specifications you've requested.","durationMs":5149,"url":"https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen3/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f0521d81-a20f-41c8-bdae-2bbd29900a5f","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"014ec21b-5611-447e-94cd-263153e05032","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Mu6z1bFpuRSv2gSuNsVtRv","type":"tool_result","content":"# Thinking Budget Guidance from Qwen3 Documentation\n\n## Recommended Values\n\nThe documentation provides example parameters but no explicit \"recommended\" values:\n- **thinking_budget**: 512 tokens (example used)\n- **max_tokens**: 1024 tokens (example used)\n\n## Interaction with Output Length\n\nThe thinking budget directly reduces available tokens for the final response. The code enforces this relationship:\n\n> \"thinking budget must be smaller than maximum new tokens\"\n\nAfter the reasoning phase, \"remaining_tokens = max_tokens - reasoning_tokens_len\" determines how many tokens remain for the actual response. The implementation requires remaining tokens to stay positive.\n\n## Reasoning Length Guidance\n\nThe documentation **does not provide specific guidance** on how much reasoning length different task types (arithmetic, multi-step reasoning, etc.) require. \n\nThe only contextual hint appears when reasoning content exceeds the budget:\n\n> \"Considering the limited time by the user, I have to give the solution based on the thinking directly now.\"\n\nThis suggests the system can operate under constrained reasoning budgets, but optimal lengths per task type are not documented in this file."}]},"uuid":"ede7176d-233c-410e-b5e5-61b3e754d8a9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:45:45.782Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":281428,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Thinking Budget Guidance from Qwen3 Documentation\n\n## Recommended Values\n\nThe documentation provides example parameters but no explicit \"recommended\" values:\n- **thinking_budget**: 512 tokens (example used)\n- **max_tokens**: 1024 tokens (example used)\n\n## Interaction with Output Length\n\nThe thinking budget directly reduces available tokens for the final response. The code enforces this relationship:\n\n> \"thinking budget must be smaller than maximum new tokens\"\n\nAfter the reasoning phase, \"remaining_tokens = max_tokens - reasoning_tokens_len\" determines how many tokens remain for the actual response. The implementation requires remaining tokens to stay positive.\n\n## Reasoning Length Guidance\n\nThe documentation **does not provide specific guidance** on how much reasoning length different task types (arithmetic, multi-step reasoning, etc.) require. \n\nThe only contextual hint appears when reasoning content exceeds the budget:\n\n> \"Considering the limited time by the user, I have to give the solution based on the thinking directly now.\"\n\nThis suggests the system can operate under constrained reasoning budgets, but optimal lengths per task type are not documented in this file.","durationMs":5202,"url":"https://github.com/QwenLM/Qwen3/blob/main/docs/source/getting_started/thinking_budget.md"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"014ec21b-5611-447e-94cd-263153e05032","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"3d80efbe-7ebd-4497-8988-70dd8d0914a2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014qakxPgqnu5pTXEt2roZC3","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"in-context learning small 7B 8B model few-shot worked examples format improve rule following arithmetic\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"MatheMagic: Generating Dynamic Mathematics Benchmarks Robust to Memorization\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.05962\"},{\"title\":\"Beyond Single-Task: Robust Multi-Task Length Generalization for LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.11525\"},{\"title\":\"Stop Fine-Tuning Everything: Inject Knowledge with Few‑Shot In‑Context Learning - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/superorange0707/stop-fine-tuning-everything-inject-knowledge-with-few-shot-in-context-learning-40gb\"},{\"title\":\"What is In-Context Learning (ICL)? | IBM\",\"url\":\"https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/in-context-learning\"},{\"title\":\"How well do Large Language Models perform in Arithmetic tasks?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2304.02015\"},{\"title\":\"Few-Shot Learning for LLMs: Examples and Implementation Guide\",\"url\":\"https://tetrate.io/learn/ai/few-shot-learning-llms\"},{\"title\":\"Case-Based or Rule-Based: How Do Transformers Do the Math?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.17709\"},{\"title\":\"Evaluation of Few-Shot AI-Generated Feedback on Case Reports in Physical Therapy Education: Mixed Methods Study\",\"url\":\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC12811036/\"}]\n\nI've performed the web search on your query about in-context learning with small 7B/8B models, few-shot examples, and improving rule following and arithmetic performance.\n\nHere are the key findings from the search results:\n\n**In-Context Learning and Model Scale:**\nIn-context learning performance generally improves with model scale, and smaller models may struggle to leverage examples effectively, while larger models can extract subtle patterns from just a few demonstrations.\n\n**Few-Shot Examples and Format:**\nFew-shot prompting provides multiple examples, and chain-of-thought prompting includes intermediate reasoning steps to guide the model's logic. Instruction formatting and chain-of-thought prompting enhance arithmetic tasks by explicitly guiding the model through intermediate steps, improving accuracy compared to direct question-answer formats.\n\n**Rule Following with Examples:**\nIn-context learning requires the model to establish stronger correspondences between rules and execution traces, as it must learn to follow a new rule from just a single example. To improve this, training data can be augmented with synthetic data with unique rules assigned to each sample, which increases task diversity and encourages the model to rely on the provided rules.\n\n**Format Importance:**\nEven input/output pairs with random labels can improve performance, highlighting that the format and distribution of the prompt are as important as the labels themselves.\n\nThe search results suggest that while smaller models do struggle more with in-context learning compared to larger models, careful prompt engineering with worked examples and explicit reasoning steps can improve performance on arithmetic and rule-following tasks.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"2e3c109a-3214-4b20-8acf-0fca5e6c6047","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:45:49.488Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"in-context learning small 7B 8B model few-shot worked examples format improve rule following arithmetic","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_0179YCDzeCYCfPfM1pMB4VJC","content":[{"title":"MatheMagic: Generating Dynamic Mathematics Benchmarks Robust to Memorization","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.05962"},{"title":"Beyond Single-Task: Robust Multi-Task Length Generalization for LLMs"