{"parentUuid":"56625bda-f71a-4f24-993c-f768b44f80f7","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01A2marYAtDss4AZfQyNvYLq","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"nomic-embed-text rare symbols special tokens retrieval failure hybrid BM25 keyword embedding\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Stop the Hallucinations: Hybrid Retrieval with BM25, pgvector, embedding rerank, LLM Rubric Rerank & HyDE | by Rick Hightower | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@richardhightower/stop-the-hallucinations-hybrid-retrieval-with-bm25-pgvector-embedding-rerank-llm-rubric-rerank-895d8f7c7242\"},{\"title\":\"Ontology-Guided Neuro-Symbolic Inference: Grounding Language Models with Mathematical Domain Knowledge\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.17826\"},{\"title\":\"Feature: Knowledgebase RAG System — User-Configured Document Directory with Local Embedding, Hybrid Search & Auto-Retrieval · Issue #844 · NousResearch/hermes-agent\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/844\"},{\"title\":\"🔍 Hybrid Search (BM25 + Vector Embeddings): The Best of Both Worlds in Information Retrieval | by Mahima Agarwal | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@mahima_agarwal/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-embeddings-the-best-of-both-worlds-in-information-retrieval-0d1075fc2828\"},{\"title\":\"Ollama v0.12.5: nomic-embed-text is failing multiple times · Issue #12585 · ollama/ollama\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ollama/ollama/issues/12585\"},{\"title\":\"ReSearch: A Multi-Stage Machine Learning Framework for Earth Science Data Discovery\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.14176\"},{\"title\":\"Best Ollama Embedding Models 2026: 7 Benchmarked by MTEB Score, VRAM, and Dimensions\",\"url\":\"https://www.morphllm.com/ollama-embedding-models\"}]\n\nI've completed the web search. Here are the key findings related to your query:\n\n## Main Results Summary\n\n**Hybrid Retrieval with BM25 and Embeddings:**\nHybrid retrieval approaches combine lexical and semantic methods, addressing complementary failure modes where lexical methods miss semantically related terms, while semantic methods may return contextually similar but mathematically irrelevant symbols.\n\n**Handling Rare Symbols and Special Tokens:**\nUsers struggle with rare tokens like internal code names and SKUs when using embedding-only approaches. Lexical search (keyword indexing) never forgets an exact term.\n\n**nomic-embed-text:**\nnomic-embed-text has a native context of 8,192 tokens and has achieved 73.8M pulls on Ollama, making it one of the most popular embedding models. However, there have been reports of the nomic-embed-text model failing multiple times in the Ollama API with a 50-50 success rate in newer versions.\n\n**Performance Benefits:**\nBM25 excels at exact lexical matching while embeddings capture semantic similarity, and hybrid approaches benefit from both signals by prioritizing datasets retrieved by both methods.\n\nThe search results indicate that hybrid BM25 + embedding approaches are recommended to handle the limitations of pure embedding-based retrieval for rare tokens and special keywords.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"0e2742af-1e89-47a3-8121-03571bd34aa3","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:46:04.549Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"nomic-embed-text rare symbols special tokens retrieval failure hybrid BM25 keyword embedding","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_017aAm2UpyZFCQw8G19RmeRq","content":[{"title":"Stop the Hallucinations: Hybrid Retrieval with BM25, pgvector, embedding rerank, LLM Rubric Rerank & HyDE | by Rick Hightower | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@richardhightower/stop-the-hallucinations-hybrid-retrieval-with-bm25-pgvector-embedding-rerank-llm-rubric-rerank-895d8f7c7242"},{"title":"Ontology-Guided Neuro-Symbolic Inference: Grounding Language Models with Mathematical Domain Knowledge","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.17826"},{"title":"Feature: Knowledgebase RAG System — User-Configured Document Directory with Local Embedding, Hybrid Search & Auto-Retrieval · Issue #844 · NousResearch/hermes-agent","url":"https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/844"},{"title":"🔍 Hybrid Search (BM25 + Vector Embeddings): The Best of Both Worlds in Information Retrieval | by Mahima Agarwal | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@mahima_agarwal/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-embeddings-the-best-of-both-worlds-in-information-retrieval-0d1075fc2828"},{"title":"Ollama v0.12.5: nomic-embed-text is failing multiple times · Issue #12585 · ollama/ollama","url":"https://github.com/ollama/ollama/issues/12585"},{"title":"ReSearch: A Multi-Stage Machine Learning Framework for Earth Science Data Discovery","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.14176"},{"title":"Best Ollama Embedding Models 2026: 7 Benchmarked by MTEB Score, VRAM, and Dimensions","url":"https://www.morphllm.com/ollama-embedding-models"}]},"I've completed the web search. Here are the key findings related to your query:\n\n## Main Results Summary\n\n**Hybrid Retrieval with BM25 and Embeddings:**\nHybrid retrieval approaches combine lexical and semantic methods, addressing complementary failure modes where lexical methods miss semantically related terms, while semantic methods may return contextually similar but mathematically irrelevant symbols.\n\n**Handling Rare Symbols and Special Tokens:**\nUsers struggle with rare tokens like internal code names and SKUs when using embedding-only approaches. Lexical search (keyword indexing) never forgets an exact term.\n\n**nomic-embed-text:**\nnomic-embed-text has a native context of 8,192 tokens and has achieved 73.8M pulls on Ollama, making it one of the most popular embedding models. However, there have been reports of the nomic-embed-text model failing multiple times in the Ollama API with a 50-50 success rate in newer versions.\n\n**Performance Benefits:**\nBM25 excels at exact lexical matching while embeddings capture semantic similarity, and hybrid approaches benefit from both signals by prioritizing datasets retrieved by both methods.\n\nThe search results indicate that hybrid BM25 + embedding approaches are recommended to handle the limitations of pure embedding-based retrieval for rare tokens and special keywords."],"durationSeconds":7.844936083000153,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"56625bda-f71a-4f24-993c-f768b44f80f7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"80e2b612-11b4-4f76-bc63-376927b80997","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HVAYmbktewP3bBvz2QNMqt","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"self-consistency multiple samples majority vote small LLM arithmetic accuracy improvement\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Self-Consistency Sampling in LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-consistency-sampling\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Consistency Prompting for Robust LLM Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-consistency-prompting\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Consistency in Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-consistency-in-language-models\"},{\"title\":\"87. Self-Consistency Decoding: Voting Among Diverse Reasoning Paths | by Kiran vutukuri | Jan, 2026 | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@kiranvutukuri/87-self-consistency-decoding-voting-among-diverse-reasoning-paths-0a6aec6dd22c\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Consistency Boosts Calibration for Math Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.09849\"},{\"title\":\"Reliability-Aware Adaptive Self-Consistency for Efficient Sampling in LLM Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.02970v1\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Consistency Prompting: Enhancing AI Accuracy\",\"url\":\"https://learnprompting.org/docs/intermediate/self_consistency\"},{\"title\":\"Rating Roulette: Self-Inconsistency in LLM-As-A-Judge Frameworks\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.27106\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Consistency in LLM Reasoning: Ensemble Methods for Reliable Outputs - Calmops | AI, Cloud & Software Development Guides\",\"url\":\"https://calmops.com/algorithms/self-consistency-reasoning/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about self-consistency with multiple samples and majority voting for improving small LLM arithmetic accuracy:\n\n## Overview\n\nSelf-consistency sampling aggregates multiple reasoning paths in LLMs using majority voting to enhance accuracy and reduce errors in generated outputs. This technique samples multiple reasoning traces from LLMs and aggregates them via majority vote to enhance answer reliability.\n\n## How It Works\n\nThe \"sample-and-aggregate\" approach exploits the intuition that complex reasoning questions admit several solution paths converging on the same answer, and that true answers will be reinforced by independent chains, while errors will be inconsistent or rare.\n\n## Arithmetic and Math Improvements\n\nSelf-consistency achieves significant accuracy gains on benchmarks like GSM8K (+17.9%), SVAMP (+11.0%), and AQuA (+12.2%). More broadly, the technique has delivered substantial gains in tasks like arithmetic, commonsense QA, and mathematical proofs, with improvements up to +27.6% in some benchmarks. Results show 5–25% accuracy improvement on reasoning tasks.\n\n## Efficiency Considerations\n\nWhile effective, this approach requires sampling and aggregating multiple trajectories, leading to substantial computational overhead. Adaptive self-consistency variants have been developed that adjust the sampling budget based on observed responses to address this computational cost.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"59788714-dcb8-4da9-8d49-6a49865e7b45","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:46:05.346Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"self-consistency multiple samples majority vote small LLM arithmetic accuracy improvement","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Y5YAeYRHXg23tuknXNLCw8","content":[{"title":"Self-Consistency Sampling in LLMs","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-consistency-sampling"},{"title":"Self-Consistency Prompting for Robust LLM Reasoning","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-consistency-prompting"},{"title":"Self-Consistency in Language Models","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-consistency-in-language-models"},{"title":"87. Self-Consistency Decoding: Voting Among Diverse Reasoning Paths | by Kiran vutukuri | Jan, 2026 | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@kiranvutukuri/87-self-consistency-decoding-voting-among-diverse-reasoning-paths-0a6aec6dd22c"},{"title":"Self-Consistency Boosts Calibration for Math Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.09849"},{"title":"Reliability-Aware Adaptive Self-Consistency for Efficient Sampling in LLM Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.02970v1"},{"title":"Self-Consistency Prompting: Enhancing AI Accuracy","url":"https://learnprompting.org/docs/intermediate/self_consistency"},{"title":"Rating Roulette: Self-Inconsistency in LLM-As-A-Judge Frameworks","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.27106"},{"title":"Self-Consistency in LLM Reasoning: Ensemble Methods for Reliable Outputs - Calmops | AI, Cloud & Software Development Guides","url":"https://calmops.com/algorithms/self-consistency-reasoning/"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about self-consistency with multiple samples and majority voting for improving small LLM arithmetic accuracy:\n\n## Overview\n\nSelf-consistency sampling aggregates multiple reasoning paths in LLMs using majority voting to enhance accuracy and reduce errors in generated outputs. This technique samples multiple reasoning traces from LLMs and aggregates them via majority vote to enhance answer reliability.\n\n## How It Works\n\nThe \"sample-and-aggregate\" approach exploits the intuition that complex reasoning questions admit several solution paths converging on the same answer, and that true answers will be reinforced by independent chains, while errors will be inconsistent or rare.\n\n## Arithmetic and Math Improvements\n\nSelf-consistency achieves significant accuracy gains on benchmarks like GSM8K (+17.9%), SVAMP (+11.0%), and AQuA (+12.2%). More broadly, the technique has delivered substantial gains in tasks like arithmetic, commonsense QA, and mathematical proofs, with improvements up to +27.6% in some benchmarks. Results show 5–25% accuracy improvement on reasoning tasks.\n\n## Efficiency Considerations\n\nWhile effective, this approach requires sampling and aggregating multiple trajectories, leading to substantial computational overhead. Adaptive self-consistency variants have been developed that adjust the sampling budget based on observed responses to address this computational cost."],"durationSeconds":8.185260290999897,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"80e2b612-11b4-4f76-bc63-376927b80997","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"5c896f08-ce2f-484f-8bd1-95c8586d47c4","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CebbHcMWFcj5WkJzmWqMsM","type":"tool_result","content":"# Transformer Math: Case-Based vs. Rule-Based Reasoning\n\n## Key Finding\n\nThe document examines whether language models perform arithmetic through **case-based reasoning** (memorizing specific examples) or **rule-based reasoning** (applying learned rules to new operands).\n\nThe research indicates transformers primarily rely on **case-based pattern matching** rather than genuine rule abstraction. Models struggle to generalize arithmetic rules to operands outside their training distribution, even on simple operations.\n\n## Critical Implication\n\nA small model cannot reliably apply an explicitly-taught arithmetic rule to fresh numbers. When trained on arithmetic within a certain range, models fail catastrophically on out-of-distribution operands—suggesting they've internalized lookup patterns rather than compositional rules.\n\n## Mitigation Strategies\n\nThe document discusses several approaches:\n\n1. **Rule-Following Fine-Tuning**: Direct instruction on rules shows limited success; models revert to memorization patterns.\n\n2. **Scratchpad/Chain-of-Thought**: Intermediate reasoning steps (working through problems explicitly) improve generalization by making computation paths more explicit rather than relying on implicit pattern recall.\n\n3. **Step-by-step decomposition**: Breaking arithmetic into sequential operations helps, though gains remain modest for truly out-of-distribution cases.\n\n## Bottom Line\n\nThese findings suggest architectural limitations: transformers fundamentally excel at pattern recognition within training manifolds, not principled rule application across infinite domains.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 9.3MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782020763231-l4idkg.pdf]"}]},"uuid":"52a29390-72e6-4d00-9205-762a1e71cb1e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:46:09.058Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":9724387,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Transformer Math: Case-Based vs. Rule-Based Reasoning\n\n## Key Finding\n\nThe document examines whether language models perform arithmetic through **case-based reasoning** (memorizing specific examples) or **rule-based reasoning** (applying learned rules to new operands).\n\nThe research indicates transformers primarily rely on **case-based pattern matching** rather than genuine rule abstraction. Models struggle to generalize arithmetic rules to operands outside their training distribution, even on simple operations.\n\n## Critical Implication\n\nA small model cannot reliably apply an explicitly-taught arithmetic rule to fresh numbers. When trained on arithmetic within a certain range, models fail catastrophically on out-of-distribution operands—suggesting they've internalized lookup patterns rather than compositional rules.\n\n## Mitigation Strategies\n\nThe document discusses several approaches:\n\n1. **Rule-Following Fine-Tuning**: Direct instruction on rules shows limited success; models revert to memorization patterns.\n\n2. **Scratchpad/Chain-of-Thought**: Intermediate reasoning steps (working through problems explicitly) improve generalization by making computation paths more explicit rather than relying on implicit pattern recall.\n\n3. **Step-by-step decomposition**: Breaking arithmetic into sequential operations helps, though gains remain modest for truly out-of-distribution cases.\n\n## Bottom Line\n\nThese findings suggest architectural limitations: transformers fundamentally excel at pattern recognition within training manifolds, not principled rule application across infinite domains.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 9.3MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782020763231-l4idkg.pdf]","durationMs":13288,"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.17709"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"5c896f08-ce2f-484f-8bd1-95c8586d47c4","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
