{"parentUuid":"2ef4c0f5-afe8-4565-8217-0f572b759980","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019QuRwqFiDMsxrDoZETLR7H","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"benchmark in-context rule learning told rule novel operation cold fail learnability instruction following test design\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"(PDF) CL-bench: A Benchmark for Context Learning\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/400415422_CL-bench_A_Benchmark_for_Context_Learning\"},{\"title\":\"Advancing Multimodal In-Context Learning in Large Vision-Language Models   with Task-aware Demonstrations\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.04839\"},{\"title\":\"Beyond Instruction Following: Evaluating Rule Following of Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2407.08440v1\"},{\"title\":\"Is In-Context Learning Sufficient for Instruction Following in LLMs?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2405.19874\"},{\"title\":\"GMP: A Benchmark for Content Moderation under Co-occurring Violations and Dynamic Rules\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.01724\"},{\"title\":\"In-context Interference in Chat-based Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2309.12727\"},{\"title\":\"Beyond Single-Task: Robust Multi-Task Length Generalization for LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.11525\"},{\"title\":\"Improving In-Context Learning with Reasoning Distillation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.10647\"},{\"title\":\"AQA-Bench: An Interactive Benchmark for Evaluating LLMs' Sequential Reasoning Ability\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.09404\"},{\"title\":\"When Thinking Fails: The Pitfalls of Reasoning for Instruction-Following in LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.11423\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found several relevant research papers and benchmarks related to in-context rule learning and instruction following:\n\n## Key Findings:\n\n**Benchmarks for In-Context Learning:**\n\nCL-bench is a benchmark that measures context learning across different subcategories, with rule system application showing varying performance rates, where legal & regulatory subcategories achieve solving rates exceeding 29%, while mathematical formalism proves far more difficult with most models falling below 15%.\n\nICLEval is designed to assess the in-context learning (ICL) abilities of large language models, focusing on two main sub-abilities: exact copying and rule learning, which evaluates how well LLMs can derive and apply rules from examples in the context.\n\n**Rule Learning and Instruction Following:**\n\nStrong performance on existing long context and instruction following benchmarks does not guarantee success on context learning benchmarks, as context learning further demands that models internalize novel knowledge and apply it flexibly to solve complex tasks.\n\nRuleBench is a comprehensive benchmark created to evaluate a diversified range of rule-following abilities.\n\n**Common Failure Modes:**\n\nThe majority of solving failures are attributed to ignoring knowledge in the context or incorrectly applying contextual knowledge, with a considerable proportion of errors also stemming from instruction-following failures resulting in incorrect output formats.\n\nThese benchmarks and evaluation frameworks are designed to test how well language models can learn new rules from context and apply them to novel tasks.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"e5674a77-558a-416e-afe7-528183072331","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:46:34.653Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"benchmark in-context rule learning told rule novel operation cold fail learnability instruction following test design","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Jw5EZymw4bqxPbat8uBKD2","content":[{"title":"(PDF) CL-bench: A Benchmark for Context Learning","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/400415422_CL-bench_A_Benchmark_for_Context_Learning"},{"title":"Advancing Multimodal In-Context Learning in Large Vision-Language Models   with Task-aware Demonstrations","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.04839"},{"title":"Beyond Instruction Following: Evaluating Rule Following of Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2407.08440v1"},{"title":"Is In-Context Learning Sufficient for Instruction Following in LLMs?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2405.19874"},{"title":"GMP: A Benchmark for Content Moderation under Co-occurring Violations and Dynamic Rules","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.01724"},{"title":"In-context Interference in Chat-based Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2309.12727"},{"title":"Beyond Single-Task: Robust Multi-Task Length Generalization for LLMs","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.11525"},{"title":"Improving In-Context Learning with Reasoning Distillation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.10647"},{"title":"AQA-Bench: An Interactive Benchmark for Evaluating LLMs' Sequential Reasoning Ability","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.09404"},{"title":"When Thinking Fails: The Pitfalls of Reasoning for Instruction-Following in LLMs","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.11423"}]},"Based on the search results, I found several relevant research papers and benchmarks related to in-context rule learning and instruction following:\n\n## Key Findings:\n\n**Benchmarks for In-Context Learning:**\n\nCL-bench is a benchmark that measures context learning across different subcategories, with rule system application showing varying performance rates, where legal & regulatory subcategories achieve solving rates exceeding 29%, while mathematical formalism proves far more difficult with most models falling below 15%.\n\nICLEval is designed to assess the in-context learning (ICL) abilities of large language models, focusing on two main sub-abilities: exact copying and rule learning, which evaluates how well LLMs can derive and apply rules from examples in the context.\n\n**Rule Learning and Instruction Following:**\n\nStrong performance on existing long context and instruction following benchmarks does not guarantee success on context learning benchmarks, as context learning further demands that models internalize novel knowledge and apply it flexibly to solve complex tasks.\n\nRuleBench is a comprehensive benchmark created to evaluate a diversified range of rule-following abilities.\n\n**Common Failure Modes:**\n\nThe majority of solving failures are attributed to ignoring knowledge in the context or incorrectly applying contextual knowledge, with a considerable proportion of errors also stemming from instruction-following failures resulting in incorrect output formats.\n\nThese benchmarks and evaluation frameworks are designed to test how well language models can learn new rules from context and apply them to novel tasks."],"durationSeconds":7.424033749999478,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2ef4c0f5-afe8-4565-8217-0f572b759980","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"c851d847-a44a-443c-ad80-6cfc5e32dbcc","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"86e3c656-fdf4-40b7-9b8a-223e791a3151","agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FJxryL2UbAHktmLGVqC5Tr","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"sentence embedding models tokenizer rare unicode symbol out of vocabulary semantic search exact match keyword fallback\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Tokenization for Natural Language Processing | by Srinivas Chakravarthy | TDS Archive | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/data-science/tokenization-for-natural-language-processing-a179a891bad4\"},{\"title\":\"Tokens And Embeddings: The Foundation of Language Models. | by Lokesh Gaur | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@gaurlokesh1211/tokens-and-embeddings-the-foundation-of-language-models-a48bbdc89004\"},{\"title\":\"SentencePiece: Subword Tokenization with BPE and Unigram - Interactive | Michael Brenndoerfer | Michael Brenndoerfer\",\"url\":\"https://mbrenndoerfer.com/writing/sentencepiece-subword-tokenization-bpe-unigram\"},{\"title\":\"ReasonCD: A Multimodal Reasoning Large Model for Implicit Change-of-Interest Semantic Mining\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.19354\"},{\"title\":\"Unsupervised Sentence Compression using Denoising Auto-Encoders\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1809.02669\"},{\"title\":\"Parameter-free Sentence Embedding via Orthogonal Basis\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1810.00438\"},{\"title\":\"Tokenization algorithms · Hugging Face\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/tokenizer_summary\"},{\"title\":\"Tokenizer Training: HuggingFace Custom NLP Tokenizer Guide - Interactive | Michael Brenndoerfer | Michael Brenndoerfer\",\"url\":\"https://mbrenndoerfer.com/writing/tokenizer-training-guide-huggingface-custom-nlp\"},{\"title\":\"SentencePiece for Language Agnostic Tokenization\",\"url\":\"https://apxml.com/courses/how-to-build-a-large-language-model/chapter-5-tokenization-large-vocabularies/sentencepiece-implementation\"},{\"title\":\"Vinija's Notes • Natural Language Processing • Tokenizer\",\"url\":\"https://vinija.ai/nlp/tokenizer/\"}]\n\nI've completed the web search for your query. Here are the results:\n\nThe search returned comprehensive information about sentence embedding models, tokenizers, and how they handle out-of-vocabulary (OOV) words and rare Unicode symbols:\n\n**Key Findings:**\n\n1. **Out-of-Vocabulary Handling**: Out-of-vocabulary (OOV) words are typically projected to a special \"UNK\" token, but this causes different OOV words with drastically different meanings to share the same embedding. One approach is to map OOVs to pretrained in-vocabulary words using a hash function, so different OOV words have different embeddings.\n\n2. **Rare Unicode and Special Characters**: With over 140,000 Unicode characters, a vocabulary of 32,000 tokens cannot cover all rare scripts. Any character not in the base vocabulary maps to an unknown token, though in practice the base vocabulary covers all characters seen during training, making unknown tokens rare.\n\n3. **Semantic Search**: Sentence embedding vectors can be compared to find similar sentences, cluster documents by topic, or build semantic search systems that understand meaning rather than just matching keywords.\n\n4. **Subword Tokenization**: For words not present or with low frequency in training data, BPE splits them into multiple common subword units, improving the model's generalization to rare or new words.\n\n5. **Byte-Level BPE**: Byte-level BPE uses 256 byte values as the base vocabulary instead, ensuring every word can be tokenized without the \"<unk>\" token.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"c8ad6e0d-d65c-48cb-ac99-e8d9076eadd3","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:46:36.469Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"sentence embedding models tokenizer rare unicode symbol out of vocabulary semantic search exact match keyword fallback","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_015ZBpZjpJmm6Vj1NTukXf98","content":[{"title":"Tokenization for Natural Language Processing | by Srinivas Chakravarthy | TDS Archive | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/data-science/tokenization-for-natural-language-processing-a179a891bad4"},{"title":"Tokens And Embeddings: The Foundation of Language Models. | by Lokesh Gaur | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@gaurlokesh1211/tokens-and-embeddings-the-foundation-of-language-models-a48bbdc89004"},{"title":"SentencePiece: Subword Tokenization with BPE and Unigram - Interactive | Michael Brenndoerfer | Michael Brenndoerfer","url":"https://mbrenndoerfer.com/writing/sentencepiece-subword-tokenization-bpe-unigram"},{"title":"ReasonCD: A Multimodal Reasoning Large Model for Implicit Change-of-Interest Semantic Mining","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.19354"},{"title":"Unsupervised Sentence Compression using Denoising Auto-Encoders","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1809.02669"},{"title":"Parameter-free Sentence Embedding via Orthogonal Basis","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1810.00438"},{"title":"Tokenization algorithms · Hugging Face","url":"https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/tokenizer_summary"},{"title":"Tokenizer Training: HuggingFace Custom NLP Tokenizer Guide - Interactive | Michael Brenndoerfer | Michael Brenndoerfer","url":"https://mbrenndoerfer.com/writing/tokenizer-training-guide-huggingface-custom-nlp"},{"title":"SentencePiece for Language Agnostic Tokenization","url":"https://apxml.com/courses/how-to-build-a-large-language-model/chapter-5-tokenization-large-vocabularies/sentencepiece-implementation"},{"title":"Vinija's Notes • Natural Language Processing • Tokenizer","url":"https://vinija.ai/nlp/tokenizer/"}]},"I've completed the web search for your query. Here are the results:\n\nThe search returned comprehensive information about sentence embedding models, tokenizers, and how they handle out-of-vocabulary (OOV) words and rare Unicode symbols:\n\n**Key Findings:**\n\n1. **Out-of-Vocabulary Handling**: Out-of-vocabulary (OOV) words are typically projected to a special \"UNK\" token, but this causes different OOV words with drastically different meanings to share the same embedding. One approach is to map OOVs to pretrained in-vocabulary words using a hash function, so different OOV words have different embeddings.\n\n2. **Rare Unicode and Special Characters**: With over 140,000 Unicode characters, a vocabulary of 32,000 tokens cannot cover all rare scripts. Any character not in the base vocabulary maps to an unknown token, though in practice the base vocabulary covers all characters seen during training, making unknown tokens rare.\n\n3. **Semantic Search**: Sentence embedding vectors can be compared to find similar sentences, cluster documents by topic, or build semantic search systems that understand meaning rather than just matching keywords.\n\n4. **Subword Tokenization**: For words not present or with low frequency in training data, BPE splits them into multiple common subword units, improving the model's generalization to rare or new words.\n\n5. **Byte-Level BPE**: Byte-level BPE uses 256 byte values as the base vocabulary instead, ensuring every word can be tokenized without the \"<unk>\" token."],"durationSeconds":8.943514208000153,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c851d847-a44a-443c-ad80-6cfc5e32dbcc","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"c8ad6e0d-d65c-48cb-ac99-e8d9076eadd3","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8795bfae9e2c2e2b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_014BBAjxa2dApbaWW4A823MC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have thorough coverage across all five areas. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Research findings: turning Yogi's 0.10 skill-transfer into a certifiable lift on qwen3:8b\n\nThe single highest-confidence finding: **`/no_think` is almost certainly the primary cause.** Every other suspect is real but secondary. Below, each section ends with the implication for Yogi, and the report closes with a cheapest-first recommendation.\n\n## 1. Thinking vs no-think for rule application / arithmetic\n\nThis is the load-bearing finding. Applying `a⊕b = a*b + a + b` to fresh operands is a multi-step arithmetic computation, and `/no_think` removes exactly the scratchpad the model needs.\n\n- **Disabling thinking causes large drops on math.** Adding no-think supervision to Qwen3-8B drops GSM8K 93.0%→90.3% and **AIME24 76.6%→43.3%**; even 1% no-think data measurably hurts reasoning fidelity. The harder/more multi-step the task, the bigger the collapse. ([arxiv 2511.03408](https://arxiv.org/html/2511.03408v1))\n- **Thinking is the most compute-efficient way to get accuracy** across 0.6B/1.7B/4B scales — highest accuracy for a modest 1.3–2.9x FLOP increase. ([arxiv 2511.03408](https://arxiv.org/html/2511.03408v1))\n- **Transformers do arithmetic case-based, not rule-based** — they pattern-match memorized cases and fail out-of-distribution; the documented mitigation that actually helps is **scratchpad / step-by-step chain-of-thought**, which makes the computation path explicit instead of relying on implicit recall. A told rule applied silently (no_think) is precisely the failure mode this paper predicts. ([arxiv 2402.17709](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.17709))\n- **Token budget:** Qwen's official guidance recommends **32,768 output tokens** for normal thinking queries (38,912 for hard math). The thinking-budget docs use thinking_budget=512 with max_tokens=1024 as a minimal example, and thinking_budget must be < max_tokens. For your simple 2-operand arithmetic, thinking is short — but you must give real headroom: budget ~**512–1024 thinking tokens, max_tokens ~1536–2048**. If the budget is too small the model emits \"Considering the limited time… I have to give the solution directly,\" which reproduces a no-think failure. ([thinking_budget.md](https://github.com/QwenLM/Qwen3/blob/main/docs/source/getting_started/thinking_budget.md), [Qwen3-8B card](https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-8B))\n- **Sampling matters:** Qwen explicitly says **DO NOT use greedy decoding** in thinking mode (causes degradation/repetition). Use thinking-mode params: **temp 0.6, top_p 0.95, top_k 20, min_p 0**. (Non-thinking is temp 0.7, top_p 0.8.) ([Qwen3-8B card](https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-8B), [muxup quick reference](https://muxup.com/2025q2/recommended-llm-parameter-quick-reference))\n- **Trade-offs:** thinking is 2–3x more output tokens and proportionally more latency; memory is unchanged (same weights, just more KV cache for longer generations — negligible at these lengths on 16 GB).\n\n**For Yogi:** the proposer prefixing `/no_think` is the prime suspect and the cheapest fix. Drop it for the apply step; switch to thinking-mode sampling params and adequate max_tokens.\n\n## 2. Formatting an in-context skill so a small model reliably applies it\n\n- **Chain-of-thought / instruction formatting beats direct Q→A** for arithmetic in small models — explicit intermediate-step guidance improves accuracy over direct answer formats. ([arxiv 2304.02015](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2304.02015), [IBM ICL](https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/in-context-learning))\n- **Worked examples (few-shot) are critical at 7–8B** — small models struggle to leverage rules from a bare statement; the format and distribution of demonstrations matter as much as the content. Include 1–3 fully-worked `⊕` examples *with the substitution shown* (e.g. `3⊕4 = 3*4 + 3 + 4 = 12+7 = 19`). ([dev.to few-shot ICL](https://dev.to/superorange0707/stop-fine-tuning-everything-inject-knowledge-with-few-shot-in-context-learning-40gb), [arxiv 2402.17709](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.17709))\n- **Give a step-by-step template + output-format constraint.** A dominant failure mode in rule-following benchmarks is *correct reasoning, wrong output format* — so specify \"show substitution, then compute, then put the final number on a line `ANSWER: <n>`,\" and parse that line. ([RuleBench/CL-bench summary](https://arxiv.org/html/2407.08440v1))\n- **Caution: \"show work then answer\" interacts with thinking.** \"When Thinking Fails\" shows reasoning can sometimes *hurt* strict instruction-following — so keep the apply prompt's instructions simple and let thinking handle the arithmetic, rather than stacking many format rules. ([arxiv 2505.11423](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.11423))\n\n**For Yogi:** the skill note should not be a terse rule string. Make it: definition + 2–3 worked examples showing the substitution + a one-line answer-format constraint.\n\n## 3. Retrieval reliability for the rare `⊕` symbol\n\n- **Pure embedding retrieval is weak on rare symbols/exact tokens.** Embedding models miss rare exact terms (SKUs, code names, symbols); lexical search \"never forgets an exact term.\" Rare Unicode like `⊕` is the worst case for a subword/SentencePiece tokenizer — it may map to byte fragments or a near-UNK representation, so two `⊕` strings won't reliably cluster semantically. ([morphllm/embeddings](https://medium.com/@mahima_agarwal/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-embeddings-the-best-of-both-worlds-in-information-retrieval-0d1075fc2828), [HF tokenizer summary](https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/tokenizer_summary))\n- **Hybrid (BM25/keyword + embedding) is the standard fix** for exactly this complementary failure: lexical catches the exact `⊕`, embedding catches paraphrase. ([Hightower hybrid retrieval](https://medium.com/@richardhightower/stop-the-hallucinations-hybrid-retrieval-with-bm25-pgvector-embedding-rerank-llm-rubric-rerank-895d8f7c7242))\n- **Operational note:** there are recent reports of nomic-embed-text intermittently failing (~50% success) in newer Ollama versions — worth ruling out as a confound. ([ollama #12585](https://github.com/ollama/ollama/issues/12585))\n\n**For Yogi:** don't gate a *transfer-mechanism* certification on retrieval. For the bench, **inject the skill deterministically when the task-class is detected** (separate the retrieve question from the apply question — see §4). Separately, for the production memory path, add a **keyword/exact-symbol index alongside the embedding** so `⊕` queries hit reliably.\n\n## 4. Other variations to make 8B token-space transfer work\n\n- **Self-consistency (sample k, majority vote)** is the highest-ROI accuracy lever for small-model arithmetic: +17.9% GSM8K, +11% SVAMP, up to +27.6% on some reasoning benchmarks; typical 5–25% lift. With thinking + a told rule, k=5 votes should push a borderline result over a certification threshold. Adaptive self-consistency caps cost on easy items. ([emergentmind self-consistency](https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-consistency-sampling), [arxiv 2403.09849](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.09849), [arxiv 2601.02970](https://arxiv.org/html/2601.02970v1))\n- **Separate \"retrieve\" from \"apply.\"** Benchmarks confirm two distinct failure modes — *ignoring context knowledge* vs *misapplying it* vs *format errors*. Measuring them separately tells you whether 0.10 is a retrieval miss or an application failure. Certify apply with the rule injected; measure retrieval as its own metric. ([ICLEval/CL-bench summary](https://arxiv.org/html/2407.08440v1))\n- **Verification / self-check** adds a small lift and pairs well with the answer-format line (re-derive and compare).\n- **Simpler vs richer notes:** richer (worked examples) > terse for a weak ICL model — but avoid over-stuffing format rules (§2 caveat).\n- **Larger student / distillation:** real but last-resort given the 16 GB / one-model rule — try config + prompt fixes first; only consider a stronger student if thinking+few-shot+vote still fails.\n\n## 5. Designing a bench that is both cold-failing AND applicable\n\nThe risk is choosing a task where even *with* the rule the 8B model fails — that can never certify. Guidance:\n\n- **Pick tasks in the \"told rule reliably lifts\" zone.** CL-bench shows rule-application solve rates vary hugely by type: legal/regulatory rules >29%, **mathematical formalism <15%** for most models. Heavy *multi-step* arithmetic-formalism is the hardest case — your `⊕` with large operands risks landing there. ([CL-bench](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/400415422_CL-bench_A_Benchmark_for_Context_Learning))\n- **Make the operation cold-novel (you have this) but keep the per-instance computation cheap.** Use **small operands** (single/low double digits) so applying the rule is 2–3 trivial steps — this isolates \"did it use the told rule\" from \"can it do big arithmetic.\" A model that fails cold but succeeds-with-rule on small operands is the textbook certifiable-transfer case.\n- **Always probe a learnability ceiling first:** before certifying, run the same items with the rule given few-shot + thinking + vote. If that ceiling isn't ~0.8+, the task is in the \"even-with-rule-fails\" zone — pick an easier transfer task for first certification. ICLEval's split (exact-copy vs rule-learning) is a good template. ([ICLEval/arxiv 2407.08440](https://arxiv.org/html/2407.08440v1))\n\n---\n\n# Recommendation for Yogi — cheapest-first\n\n1. **Turn OFF `/no_think` on the apply step; switch to thinking-mode sampling and real token headroom.** Use temp 0.6 / top_p 0.95 / top_k 20 / min_p 0, never greedy, max_tokens ≥1536 (thinking_budget ~512–1024). This alone should move the needle most — it's the prime suspect and free. ([Qwen3-8B card](https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-8B), [arxiv 2511.03408](https://arxiv.org/html/2511.03408v1), [arxiv 2402.17709](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.17709))\n2. **Inject the skill deterministically for the bench** (task-class detected → rule guaranteed in context). This removes retrieval as a confound so you're certifying the transfer *mechanism*, not nomic-embed-text's handling of `⊕`. ([hybrid retrieval](https://medium.com/@richardhightower/stop-the-hallucinations-hybrid-retrieval-with-bm25-pgvector-embedding-rerank-llm-rubric-rerank-895d8f7c7242))\n3. **Reformat the skill note: definition + 2–3 worked `⊕` examples showing substitution + a `ANSWER: <n>` output line; parse that line.** Fixes both application and format-error failure modes. ([few-shot ICL](https://dev.to/superorange0707/stop-fine-tuning-everything-inject-knowledge-with-few-shot-in-context-learning-40gb), [RuleBench](https://arxiv.org/html/2407.08440v1))\n4. **Use small operands in the bench and verify a learnability ceiling (rule given + thinking + vote ≈ 0.8+) before certifying.** Ensures the task is in the applicable zone, not mathematical-formalism-hard. ([CL-bench](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/400415422_CL-bench_A_Benchmark_for_Context_Learning), [ICLEval](https://arxiv.org/html/2407.08440v1))\n5. **Add self-consistency (k=5, majority vote)** on the apply step for the final margin; adaptive cap to control the extra inference cost. ([self-consistency](https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-consistency-sampling), [arxiv 2403.09849](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.09849))\n6. **Separately (production path, not the cert): add a keyword/exact-symbol index alongside the embedding** so `⊕` retrieves reliably, and rule out the nomic-embed-text intermittent-failure bug in your Ollama version. ([ollama #12585](https://github.com/ollama/ollama/issues/12585))\n7. **Last resort only:** a stronger student / distillation if 1–5 still under-certify — gated by the 16 GB one-model-at-a-time rule. ([arxiv 2511.03408](https://arxiv.org/html/2511.03408v1))\n\nExpected effect: steps 1–3 are very likely sufficient on their own to move 0.10 well past a cold 0.00 into certifiable territory; step 5 buys headroom; step 4 protects you from certifying against an impossible task.\n\nNote: I did not edit any files, per the request — these are findings/recommendations only. The most relevant Yogi files to apply changes in are the proposer crate (the `/no_think` prefix and sampling params) and `being-bench` (deterministic skill injection, operand sizing, learnability-ceiling probe, vote), but I leave the implementation to you."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3307,"cache_read_input_tokens":24200,"output_tokens":4934,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3307},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":4934,"cache_read_input_tokens":24200,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3307,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3307,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFsojhtXzdr77t6oc1vv","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"339420a7-acd7-48ef-8980-43bff1c0815a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:47:43.332Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
